'''Howard V. Tayler''' (born February 29, 1968 in [[Florida]])<ref name="schlock-bio">{{cite web|url=http://www.schlockmercenary.com/schlock_author.html|title=Howard V. Tayler: Author, creator, and "artist" for ''Schlock Mercenary''|first=Howard|last=Tayler|publisher=The Tayler Corporation|accessdate=April 21, 2010|archivedate=April 21, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5p9O1HBGK}}</ref> is the award-winning creator of the hugely successful<ref name="comix411">{{cite web|url=http://comics.gearlive.com/comix411/article/q308-hugo-awards-neil-gaiman-phil-foglio-howard-tayler/|title=Hugo Awards: Neil Gaiman, Phil Foglio, Howard Tayler and Captain Britain|first=Tom|last=Mason|date=April 7, 2010|publisher=Comics 411|accessdate=April 21, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5p9K1hB08|archivedate=April 21, 2010}}</ref> [[webcomic]] ''[[Schlock Mercenary]]''. He worked as a volunteer missionary for the [[LDS Church]], then graduated from [[Brigham Young University]].<ref name="schlock-bio"/> Using his degree in [[Musical composition|music composition]], he started an independent record label. 

While working at [[Novell]], Tayler began online publication of ''Schlock Mercenary''. He quit his job at Novell several years later in order to work on the webcomic [[Full-time|full time]].<ref name="daily-herald2009"/> ''Schlock Mercenary'' has been nominated multiple times and won the [[Web Cartoonists' Choice Awards]] in two different categories. The webcomic has also been nominated twice for a [[Hugo Award]]. 

Tayler spends time regularly during the week drawing at a local comic book and gaming store.<ref name="daily-herald2009"/>

==Biography==
Tayler was born in Florida. In 1985 he moved to [[Utah]] (where he still resides) to attend [[Brigham Young University]]. After studying there for two years, he volunteered to be a [[Missionary (LDS Church)|missionary]] for [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS) before returning to BYU to finish a Bachelor's degree in [[Musical composition|Music Composition]].<ref name="schlock-bio"/> 

He co-founded an independant record label called ''Sanctus Records'',<ref name="schlock-bio"/> which was aimed primarily at an LDS market. Tayler also worked for [[Novell]] as a project manager,<ref name="daily-cartoonist">{{cite web|url=http://dailycartoonist.com/index.php/2009/02/12/howard-taylors-journey-to-profitable-webcomics/|title=Howard Tayler's journey to profitable webcomics|publisher=The Daily Cartoonist|first=Alan|last=Gardner|date=February 12, 2009|accessdate=April 21, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5p9Ld3MpH|archivedate=April 21, 2010}}</ref> where he co-authored a guide to administering [[GroupWise]].<ref name="schlock-bio"/> 

In 2000, he began publishing his webcomic, ''[[Schlock Mercenary]]''. Four years later, Tayler left his job as product line manager at Novell in order to work full time on the webcomic.<ref name="schlock-bio"/> By 2009, he was able to make enough from the sales of the compilation books and other merchandise to make ends meet and reduce his weekly workload from 80-100 hours down to 40-50.<ref name="daily-herald2009">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/article_634a85c6-4f1a-5033-926b-fad53bbaff68.html|title=Orem cartoonist a rising figure in Web-comic world|first=Michael|last=Rigert|publisher=''[[Daily Herald (Utah)|The Daily Herald]]''|date=February 11, 2009|accessdate=April 21, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5p9MgpE6v|archivedate=April 21, 2010}}</ref>

Since February 10, 2008, Tayler has produced a writing tips [[podcast]] with best-selling fantasy author [[Brandon Sanderson]] and horror author [[Dan Wells (author)|Dan Wells]].<ref name="writing-excuses">{{cite web|url=http://www.writingexcuses.com/2008/02/10/writing-excuses-episode-1-brainstorming/|title=Writing Excuses Episode 1: Brainstorming|date=February 10, 2008|accessdate=April 21, 2010|archivedate=April 21, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5p9NUhoTV}}</ref>

He has been a guest of honor at many genre conventions, including [[Balticon]], [[CONduit (convention)|CONduit]], [[LepreCon]], and [[Life, the Universe, & Everything]]. His wife, Sandra, is also a published author.<ref name="daily-herald2009"/>

==Works==
In March 2000, Tayler coauthored with Ross Phillips and Tay Kratzer the guidebook ''Administering GroupWise 5.5'', written to assist [[system administrator]]s in managing Novell's [[GroupWise]]. 

Tayler's most well-known work is his webcomic, ''[[Schlock Mercenary]]'', a comedic [[webcomic]] which follows the tribulations of a star-travelling [[mercenary]] company in a satiric, mildly [[dystopia]]n 31st-century [[space opera]] setting. The story primarily centers on [[List of Schlock Mercenary characters#Captain Kaff Tagon|Captain Kaff Tagon]] and his mercenary crew, Tagon's Toughs. Members of the crew include resident mad scientist and munitions commander [[List of Schlock Mercenary characters#Captain Kevyn Andreyasn (Retired)/Munitions Commander Kevyn Andreyasn (Active Duty)|Kevyn Andreyasn]], the title [[Schlock Mercenary characters#Amorphs|carbosillicate amorph]] [[List of Schlock Mercenary characters#Sergeant Schlock|Sergeant Schlock]], former artificial intelligence [[List of Schlock Mercenary characters#Post-Dated Check Loan (or "Petey")|Petey]], and the wry [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] and former [[boyband]], [[List of Schlock Mercenary characters#Adjutant Ennesby|Ennesby]].

Many plotlines revolve around the jobs Tagon and his crew have accepted. Other times, the crew is swept up in a galaxy- or universe-spanning conflict. Since its debut on June 12, 2000 the comic has updated daily, begun to [[List of self-sufficient webcomics|support its author]],<ref name="daily-cartoonist"/> and been nominated for two [[Hugo Award]]s.<ref name="hugonom2009"/><ref name="hugonom2010"/> 

In March of 2008 Tayler, along with [[Brandon Sanderson]] and [[Dan Wells (author)|Dan Wells]] launched ''Writing Excuses'', a podcast for aspiring writers. The 15-minute 'cast has been running weekly since that time, and has featured a number of notable guests including [[Steve Jackson]], [[Phil Foglio]], [[Brandon Mull]], [[Tracy Hickman]], and [[Patrick Rothfuss]].<ref name="writing-excuses"/>

Along with best-selling fantasy author [[Tracy Hickman]] and his son, [[Curtis Hickman|Curtis]], he illustrated and published ''XDM X-Treme Dungeon Mastery'', a guide for [[gamemaster]]s who want to focus more on the fun aspects of [[roleplaying game]]s rather than the mechanics of counting everything.<ref name="roleplaying-pro">{{cite web|url=http://www.roleplayingpro.com/2009/07/16/xdm-x-treme-dungeon-mastery-a-dms-review/|title=XDM X-Treme Dungeon Mastery: A DM<U+2019>s Review|date=July 16, 2009|first=John|last=Lewis|publisher=Roleplaying Pro|accessdate=April 21, 2010|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5p9L1dsOQ|archivedate=April 21, 2010}}</ref>

